PUH-BrianMartell T_max Instability Formalization — Understandable Explanation The instability at maximum tension T_max is the mechanical trigger for the rebound in Theorem 8. When all knots amalgamate into a single super-Planck core, local tension T reaches a critical value T_max beyond which the lattice can no longer remain stable. Simple picture: •  Normal regime: T < T_max → linear ripple propagation, stable cores. •  At T = T_max → nonlinear self-interaction terms dominate → effective negative stiffness → exponential mode growth → rupture. •  Rupture releases stored tension as outward ripple burst → new expanding domains. Formalization: •  Lattice action includes nonlinear term ∝ T u^4 (self-focusing). •  Stability analysis: dispersion relation develops imaginary frequency ω² < 0 when T > T_max. •  Result: runaway instability → core ruptures, tension drops, cycle restarts. This makes the rebound inevitable and mechanical — no ad hoc bounce.
